%[text] # UPS Supported Data Center Low Voltage Ride-Through  
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%[text] ## 1. Overview
%[text] This example evaluates the ride-through capability of a uninterruptible power supply (UPS) supported data center under representative transmission-level voltage disturbances based on multiple international grid-code Low Voltage Ride Through (LVRT) profiles. These profiles are representative of typical grid code requirements and are implemented based on reference \[1\]. 
%[text] Each profile captures distinct fault-clearing behavior and voltage recovery characteristics observed in practical transmission systems.
%[text] You can use this example to assess how the data center electrical system responds to severe and moderate voltage disturbances while maintaining uninterrupted supply to critical loads.
%[text] The assessment focuses on the following aspects:
%[text] - Point of common coupling (PCC) voltage behavior during the disturbance
%[text] - Continuity of critical load power delivery
%[text] - DC bus voltage stability
%[text] - UPS operational continuity
%[text] - ITIC/CBEMA-compatible load voltage performance \
%[text] The critical load is modeled as an aggregated lumped load connected at the UPS output bus. Since rack-level distribution and server power supply unit (PSU) dynamics are not explicitly represented, the UPS output voltage serves as a proxy for IT equipment supply voltage for Information Technology Industry Council / Computer Business Equipment Manufacturers Association (ITIC/CBEMA) assessment \[2\].
%[text] The ITIC  curve defines acceptable voltage tolerance limits for IT equipment under voltage disturbances. It specifies the allowable magnitude and duration of voltage deviations within which typical data center loads, such as servers and power supplies, can operate without interruption or damage.
%[text] You can use the ITIC curve to evaluate whether the UPS output voltage remains within acceptable operating limits during transient events such as voltage sags, swells, and short-duration interruptions. Compliance with this curve ensures that the critical IT load continues to function reliably without triggering faults or shutdowns.
%[text] In this example, the UPS output voltage is compared against the ITIC envelope to validate that the load remains within the acceptable voltage tolerance region throughout the disturbance period.
%[text] This figure shows the ITIC envelope and the operational constraints.
plot.iticCurve %[output:08554b7c]
%[text] The LVRT disturbance is applied from 3 seconds to 7 seconds in all simulations.
%%
%[text] ## 2. Execute Simulations
lvrtProfiles = {"ERCOT", "RTEFrance", "EirGrid", "ATC", "AESO"};
simResults = lvrtTest.runAll(lvrtProfiles);
%%
%[text] ### ERCOT (Electric Reliability Council of Texas)
%[text] The ERCOT profile represents transmission disturbances typical of the Texas interconnection, where large-scale transmission faults and delayed voltage recovery events are important operational considerations.
plot.lvrtProfile(1, "ERCOT"); %[output:51542b4c]
plot.activePower(simResults{1}.logsout, [2.9 10]); %[output:86e35ec4]
plot.dcBusValues(simResults{1}.logsout, [2.9 10]); %[output:3324f8d5]
plot.lvrtAssessment(simResults{1}.logsout, 1, 'ERCOT', [2.9 10]); %[output:2a4bfa89]
%%
%[text] ### RTE France
%[text] The RTE France profile represents a continuously recovering transmission voltage disturbance, creating a more demanding controller-tracking scenario compared to stepped recovery profiles.
plot.lvrtProfile(2, "RTE France"); %[output:019ef824]
plot.activePower(simResults{2}.logsout, [2.9 10]); %[output:57193096]
plot.dcBusValues(simResults{2}.logsout, [2.9 10]); %[output:3cfdc4ce]
plot.lvrtAssessment(simResults{2}.logsout, 2, 'RTE France', [2.9 10]); %[output:12d02dd9]
%%
%[text] ### Eir Grid (Ireland)
%[text] The EirGrid profile represents a severe transient disturbance scenario associated with lower-inertia power systems and high renewable penetration.

plot.lvrtProfile(3, "Eir Grid"); %[output:505a998a]
plot.activePower(simResults{3}.logsout, [2.9 10]); %[output:85a1c21c]
plot.dcBusValues(simResults{3}.logsout, [2.9 10]); %[output:9527983d]
plot.lvrtAssessment(simResults{3}.logsout,3,'Eir Grid',[2.9 10]); %[output:27055818]
%%
%[text] ### ATC (American Transmission Company)
%[text] The ATC profile represents a prolonged undervoltage recovery scenario that places sustained stress on the UPS energy storage and DC bus regulation system.
plot.lvrtProfile(4, "ATC"); %[output:06c11bb9]
plot.activePower(simResults{4}.logsout, [2.9 10]); %[output:2b2e7401]
plot.dcBusValues(simResults{4}.logsout, [2.9 10]); %[output:268b9e84]
plot.lvrtAssessment(simResults{4}.logsout, 4, 'ATC', [2.9 10]); %[output:6f31f7e1]
%%
%[text] ### AESO (Alberta Electric System Operator)
%[text] The AESO profile represents a moderate-severity sustained voltage depression scenario intended to evaluate stable operation under intermediate disturbance conditions.
plot.lvrtProfile(5, "AESO"); %[output:9291b812]
plot.activePower(simResults{5}.logsout, [2.9 10]); %[output:33f5c88b]
plot.dcBusValues(simResults{5}.logsout, [2.9 10]); %[output:532b28cf]
plot.lvrtAssessment(simResults{5}.logsout, 5, 'AESO', [2.9 10]); %[output:49b01d7d]
%%
%[text] ## 3. Overall Results
%[text] The table below shows whether the UPS breaker remained closed (PASS) or tripped open (FAIL) for each grid code during the LVRT event.
testResults = lvrtTest.evaluate(simResults, lvrtProfiles) %[output:9bd2de98]
%[text] ## 4. References
%[text] 1\. Open Compute Project Data Center Facility Power Distribution Sub-Project, Low Voltage DC (LVDC) Power Distribution White Paper v1.0, March 2026.
%[text] 2\. Voltage Disturbance, *ITIC Curve – Voltage Disturbance*, Available online: https://voltage-disturbance.com/voltage-quality/itic-curve/, accessed 2026.
